article.description: Nikki McCray scored 20 points and the Indiana Fever held Charlotte to two field goals over a 14-minute span in a 69-48 victory over the Sting on Saturday night.
article.headline: Fever within a game of fourth-place Orlando
article.linkText: Fever top Sting to remain in playoff hunt
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS -- Nikki McCray scored 20 points and the
Indiana Fever held Charlotte to two field goals over a 14-minute
span in a 69-48 victory over the Sting on Saturday night.

	   Tamika Catchings had 14 points and a career-high 15 rebounds,
and Nadine Malcom scored 12 points for the Fever (12-15), who moved
to within one game of fourth-place Orlando.

	   Fever coach Nell Fortner said McCray, a three-time WNBA All-Star
who was obtained from Washington in the offseason, is hitting her
stride.

	   "She was very aggressive and really got after it,'' Fortner
said. "She's playing really well right now. She's just been trying
to find her groove, and now, she's found it.''

	   Allison Feaster and Dawn Staley scored eight points apiece for
Charlotte (14-13), which lost its fourth straight.

	   The Fever, trailing 17-16, limited Charlotte to one field goal
over the last seven minutes of the first half and one field goal
over the first seven minutes of the second half to take a 43-23
lead.

	   The Sting missed 16 of 18 shots and turned the ball over eight
times during that stretch. They hit 34.7 percent from the field for
the game.

	   "That's really excellent defense,'' McCray said. "Now, we're
recognizing mismatches better.''

	   McCray is recognizing what she can do for the Fever.

	   "I just try to play hard, focus on what I can bring to this
team,'' she said. "Nell (Fortner) is learning I need to penetrate
and drive more. Catch is opening up the lane, allowing me to create
out there.''

	   McCray said the play of power forward Malcom was the key to the
second half.

	   "Nadine scored the first eight points for us in the second
half,'' McCray said. "That was huge. That gave her confidence and
gave the team confidence.''

	   Despite missing 11 of their first 14 shots, the Fever finished
the first half with a 27-20 lead.

	   "They were all on their `A' game, and we did not respond,''
Sting coach Anne Donovan said.
